# Merizona — Multi-Vendor Marketplace Architecture

> **Assumptions stated upfront:**
>
> 1. Scale target: hundreds–low-thousands of vendors, not millions (modular monolith, not day-1 microservices).
> 2. Production MongoDB runs as a Replica Set (Atlas or self-managed) — required for change streams and transactions.
> 3. Payment processing via Stripe Connect (Standard accounts per vendor).
> 4. Shipping aggregator (Shippo / EasyPost) rather than direct carrier APIs.
> 5. Single geographic region initially; CDN (CloudFront/Cloudflare) in front of Next.js.

---

## 1. Architecture Overview

### Component Map

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Client Layer"
        B["Browser / Mobile Web"]
    end

    subgraph "Edge / CDN"
        CF["Cloudflare / CloudFront"]
    end

    subgraph "Frontend – Next.js 16+"
        SC["Server Components (RSC)"]
        SA["Server Actions"]
        RH["Route Handlers (BFF)"]
    end

    subgraph "Backend – NestJS 11+"
        GW["HTTP Gateway (Fastify)"]
        MOD["Domain Modules"]
        WK["Bull Workers (Redis)"]
        EVT["EventEmitter2 (in-proc)"]
    end

    subgraph "Data Layer"
        MDB["MongoDB (System of Record)"]
        RD["Redis (Cache + Queues)"]
        ES["Elasticsearch (Derived Index)"]
        MIO["MinIO / S3 (Objects)"]
    end

    subgraph "External Services"
        STRIPE["Stripe (Payments)"]
        SHIPPO["Shippo (Shipping)"]
    end

    B --> CF --> SC
    SC --> |"fetch (internal network)"| GW
    SA --> |"POST (internal network)"| GW
    RH --> |"proxy/aggregate"| GW
    GW --> MOD
    MOD --> MDB
    MOD --> RD
    MOD --> ES
    MOD --> MIO
    MOD --> STRIPE
    MOD --> SHIPPO
    MOD --> EVT
    EVT --> WK
    WK --> ES
    WK --> RD
```

### Responsibilities

| Component         | Responsibility                                                                                              |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Next.js**       | SSR/SSG storefront, auth cookie management, BFF aggregation, CSRF-safe mutations via Server Actions         |
| **NestJS**        | Business logic, RBAC enforcement, data validation, background jobs (BullMQ on Redis), event-driven indexing |
| **MongoDB**       | ACID transactions for checkout, system of record for all domain data                                        |
| **Redis**         | API response cache (Keyv), BullMQ job queues, rate-limit counters, session store                            |
| **Elasticsearch** | Full-text product search, faceted filtering, autocomplete — read-only derived index                         |
| **MinIO**         | Product images, vendor logos, invoice PDFs — presigned URL upload/download                                  |
| **Stripe**        | Payment processing (Stripe Connect), vendor payouts, webhook events for payment lifecycle                   |

### Data Flow (Happy Path: Customer Purchase)

1. Browser → Next.js RSC fetches product page (cached via `fetch` + `revalidate`).
2. "Add to Cart" → Server Action → NestJS `POST /cart/items`.
3. Checkout → Server Action → NestJS `POST /orders/checkout` (MongoDB transaction: reserve inventory → create order → insert outbox event).
4. BullMQ worker picks up `OrderCreated` job → sends confirmation email, notifies vendor, triggers Shippo label creation.
5. Shippo webhook → NestJS `POST /webhooks/shipping` → updates `shipments` → pushes SSE/WebSocket event to customer tracking page.

