## 5. MongoDB Collection Design

### Entity-Relationship Overview

```mermaid
erDiagram
    users ||--o{ memberships : "has many"
    vendors ||--o{ memberships : "has many"
    vendors ||--o{ products : "sells"
    products ||--o{ inventory : "tracked by"
    users ||--o{ orders : "places"
    orders ||--o{ order_items : "contains (embedded)"
    orders ||--o{ shipments : "fulfilled by"
    vendors ||--o{ orders : "receives"
    shipments ||--o{ tracking_events : "has (embedded)"
```

### Collection Schemas

#### `users`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "email": "customer@example.com",       // unique, indexed
  "passwordHash": "...",
  "role": "customer",                     // platform_admin | customer
  "profile": {                            // EMBEDDED — always read together
    "firstName": "Jane",
    "lastName": "Doe",
    "phone": "+1...",
    "avatarUrl": "https://minio/..."
  },
  "addresses": [                          // EMBEDDED array (max 5)
    { "label": "Home", "line1": "...", "city": "...", "zip": "...", "country": "US", "isDefault": true }
  ],
  "status": "active",                     // active | suspended | deleted
  "createdAt": ISODate, "updatedAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { email: 1 } unique, { status: 1 }
```

#### `vendors`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "name": "Acme Store",
  "slug": "acme-store",                   // unique, indexed — used in URLs
  "logo": "https://minio/...",
  "status": "approved",                   // pending | approved | suspended
  "businessInfo": {                       // EMBEDDED
    "legalName": "...", "taxId": "...", "address": {...}
  },
  "stripeAccountId": "acct_...",
  "commissionRate": 0.12,                 // 12% platform commission
  "createdAt": ISODate, "updatedAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { slug: 1 } unique, { status: 1 }
```

#### `memberships` (User ↔ Vendor join)

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "userId": ObjectId,                     // REF → users
  "vendorId": ObjectId,                   // REF → vendors
  "role": "owner",                        // owner | manager | staff
  "permissions": ["manage_products", "manage_orders", "manage_settings"],
  "createdAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { userId: 1, vendorId: 1 } unique compound
```

#### `products`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "vendorId": ObjectId,                   // REF → vendors
  "title": "Wireless Headphones",
  "slug": "wireless-headphones",
  "description": "...",
  "category": ["Electronics", "Audio"],   // Array for breadcrumb
  "attributes": {                         // EMBEDDED — read with product
    "brand": "Sony", "color": "Black", "weight": "250g"
  },
  "variants": [                           // EMBEDDED array
    { "sku": "WH-BLK-M", "label": "Black / Medium", "priceInCents": 9999, "images": ["https://minio/..."] }
  ],
  "status": "published",                  // draft | published | archived
  "rating": { "avg": 4.5, "count": 120 },// Denormalized, updated async
  "createdAt": ISODate, "updatedAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { vendorId: 1, status: 1 }, { slug: 1 } unique, { "category": 1, status: 1 }
```

#### `inventory`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "productId": ObjectId,                  // REF → products
  "vendorId": ObjectId,                   // REF → vendors (denormalized for query)
  "sku": "WH-BLK-M",
  "quantityOnHand": 150,
  "quantityReserved": 12,                 // Reserved during checkout, released on cancel/timeout
  "lowStockThreshold": 10,
  "warehouseLocation": "A3-R2-S5",
  "updatedAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { sku: 1 } unique, { productId: 1 }, { vendorId: 1 }
// WHY SEPARATE: Stock changes at very high frequency (every order). Separating avoids write contention on the product document.
```

#### `orders`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "orderNumber": "MRZ-20260228-A7X3",    // Human-readable, unique
  "customerId": ObjectId,                 // REF → users
  "vendorId": ObjectId,                   // REF → vendors (one order per vendor after split)
  "items": [                              // EMBEDDED — snapshot at purchase time
    {
      "productId": ObjectId,
      "sku": "WH-BLK-M",
      "title": "Wireless Headphones",     // Snapshot — won't change if product edited
      "priceInCents": 9999,
      "quantity": 2,
      "imageUrl": "..."
    }
  ],
  "shippingAddress": { ... },             // EMBEDDED snapshot
  "subtotalInCents": 19998,
  "shippingInCents": 499,
  "taxInCents": 1800,
  "totalInCents": 22297,
  "platformCommissionInCents": 2675,
  "status": "confirmed",                  // pending | confirmed | processing | shipped | delivered | cancelled | refunded
  "paymentIntentId": "pi_...",
  "createdAt": ISODate, "updatedAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { customerId: 1, createdAt: -1 }, { vendorId: 1, status: 1 }, { orderNumber: 1 } unique
```

#### `shipments`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "orderId": ObjectId,                    // REF → orders
  "vendorId": ObjectId,
  "carrier": "fedex",
  "trackingNumber": "794644790132",
  "aggregatorShipmentId": "shp_...",      // Shippo/EasyPost ID
  "status": "in_transit",                 // pre_transit | in_transit | out_for_delivery | delivered | failure
  "estimatedDelivery": ISODate,
  "timeline": [                           // EMBEDDED array — append-only
    { "status": "label_created", "location": "New York, NY", "timestamp": ISODate, "description": "Shipping label created" },
    { "status": "in_transit", "location": "Memphis, TN", "timestamp": ISODate, "description": "Package in transit" }
  ],
  "createdAt": ISODate, "updatedAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { orderId: 1 }, { trackingNumber: 1 }
```

#### `webhook_events`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "source": "shippo",                     // shippo | stripe | ...
  "externalId": "evt_abc123",             // Idempotency key
  "eventType": "track_updated",
  "payload": { ... },                     // Raw webhook body
  "status": "processed",                  // pending | processed | failed
  "attempts": 1,
  "processedAt": ISODate,
  "createdAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { source: 1, externalId: 1 } unique (idempotency), { status: 1 } (retry query)
// TTL index: { createdAt: 1 }, expireAfterSeconds: 7776000 (90 days)
```

#### `outbox`

```jsonc
{
  "_id": ObjectId,
  "aggregateType": "order",
  "aggregateId": ObjectId,
  "eventType": "OrderCreated",
  "payload": { ... },
  "status": "pending",                    // pending | dispatched
  "createdAt": ISODate
}
// Indexes: { status: 1, createdAt: 1 }
// A poller or change stream dispatches pending events to BullMQ then marks them 'dispatched'.
```

### Embed vs Reference Decision Matrix

| Decision          | Strategy                            | Rationale                                            |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| User addresses    | **Embed** in `users`                | Always read together, bounded array (max 5)          |
| Product variants  | **Embed** in `products`             | Part of the product concept, queried together        |
| Order items       | **Embed** in `orders`               | Snapshot — must be immutable, always read with order |
| Shipment timeline | **Embed** in `shipments`            | Append-only, always displayed together               |
| Inventory         | **Reference** (separate collection) | High write frequency, avoids contention on products  |
| Memberships       | **Reference** (separate collection) | Many-to-many join between users and vendors          |

### Transactions Required

**Checkout flow** (the only multi-document transaction):

1. Decrement `inventory.quantityOnHand`, increment `quantityReserved`
2. Insert `orders` document
3. Insert `outbox` event (`OrderCreated`)

All three within a single MongoDB session/transaction. If any step fails, the entire transaction rolls back.

---

## 6. Search Indexing Plan

### What Gets Indexed

Only `products` are indexed in Elasticsearch. Orders, users, and vendors stay in MongoDB with proper indexes.

### ES Mapping (Key Fields)

```jsonc
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "productId": { "type": "keyword" },
      "vendorId": { "type": "keyword" },
      "vendorName": { "type": "keyword" },
      "title": {
        "type": "text",
        "analyzer": "autocomplete",
        "search_analyzer": "standard",
      },
      "description": { "type": "text" },
      "category": { "type": "keyword" },
      "brand": { "type": "keyword" },
      "priceInCents": { "type": "integer" },
      "rating": { "type": "float" },
      "inStock": { "type": "boolean" },
      "slug": { "type": "keyword" },
      "createdAt": { "type": "date" },
    },
  },
  "settings": {
    "analysis": {
      "analyzer": {
        "autocomplete": {
          "type": "custom",
          "tokenizer": "autocomplete_tokenizer",
          "filter": ["lowercase"],
        },
      },
      "tokenizer": {
        "autocomplete_tokenizer": {
          "type": "edge_ngram",
          "min_gram": 2,
          "max_gram": 15,
          "token_chars": ["letter", "digit"],
        },
      },
    },
  },
}
```

### Update Propagation (Outbox → BullMQ → ES)

1. CatalogModule updates product in MongoDB **+ inserts outbox event** (same transaction).
2. Outbox poller (CronJob, every 5s) picks up pending events → enqueues BullMQ `SearchIndex` job → marks event `dispatched`.
3. Worker aggregates product + vendor name + stock status → **bulk upserts** to ES (batches of 50).
4. Full reindex via CLI: `pnpm reindex:products` (creates new index, bulk inserts, swaps alias, deletes old).

**Why Outbox over Change Streams:** Simpler to reason about, participates in the same transaction, survives application restarts without resume-token management.

### Caching Strategy (Complete)

**1) Next.js fetch caching:**

| Page           | Strategy | TTL     | Invalidation                                        |
| -------------- | -------- | ------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| Homepage       | ISR      | 60s     | `revalidateTag('homepage')`                         |
| PDP            | ISR      | 300s    | `revalidateTag('product-{slug}')` on product update |
| Search results | No cache | Dynamic | User-specific query params                          |
| Category pages | ISR      | 120s    | Tag-based                                           |

**2) NestJS caching (Redis/Keyv + in-memory LRU):**

| Data                              | Layer                   | TTL   | Invalidation                            |
| --------------------------------- | ----------------------- | ----- | --------------------------------------- |
| Platform config, role definitions | In-memory LRU (50 keys) | 5min  | TTL / restart                           |
| Product detail (by slug)          | Redis Keyv              | 10min | Event-driven delete on `ProductUpdated` |
| Vendor profile                    | Redis Keyv              | 15min | Event-driven                            |
| Dashboard aggregations            | Redis Keyv              | 2min  | TTL only                                |

**3) Why NOT cache Elasticsearch in memory:**

- ES already uses OS filesystem cache (mmap) — warm queries are sub-10ms.
- Faceted search has combinatorial explosion of filter combos → cache hit rate is extremely low.
- Cached results go stale on every product update → consistency nightmare.
- **Exception:** Cache top ~50 most popular bare search terms in Redis with 5-min TTL (high hit rate, low staleness cost).

---

## 7. Delivery Tracking Integration Plan

**Decision: Use a Shipping Aggregator** (Shippo / EasyPost) — unified API for 50+ carriers, single webhook format, label generation. Engineering time saved far outweighs per-label cost.

### Flow

1. Vendor triggers "Ship Order" → NestJS calls Shippo API → gets `label_url`, `tracking_number`, `shipment_id`.
2. NestJS stores `shipments` doc, updates order status to `shipped`.
3. Carrier scans package → Shippo fires webhook → `POST /webhooks/shipping`.
4. NestJS verifies HMAC signature → checks `webhook_events` for idempotency → upserts `shipments.timeline` → enqueues notification job.
5. Customer sees live updates via SSE (`useTrackingSSE` hook → NestJS SSE endpoint).

### Webhook Verification & Idempotency

```typescript
@Post('webhooks/shipping')
async handle(@Req() req: RawBodyRequest<Request>) {
  // 1. Verify HMAC signature
  if (!verifyHmac(req.rawBody, req.headers['x-shippo-signature'], secret))
    throw new ForbiddenException('Invalid signature');
  // 2. Idempotency: skip if event already processed
  const exists = await this.webhookEvents.findByExternalId('shippo', req.body.event_id);
  if (exists) return { status: 'already_processed' };
  // 3. Process + record
  await this.webhookEvents.create({ source: 'shippo', externalId: req.body.event_id, ... });
  await this.fulfillment.processTrackingUpdate(req.body);
}
```

### Retry Policy

- Aggregator retries webhook delivery with exponential backoff (1min → 5min → 30min → 2hr).
- If NestJS processing fails after acceptance, BullMQ job retries 3× with backoff. Dead-letter jobs surface in admin dashboard.

### Timeline UI Model

```typescript
interface TrackingEvent {
  status:
    | "label_created"
    | "picked_up"
    | "in_transit"
    | "out_for_delivery"
    | "delivered"
    | "exception";
  location: string;
  timestamp: Date;
  description: string;
}
// <OrderTimeline events={shipment.timeline} estimatedDelivery={shipment.estimatedDelivery} />
// Vertical stepper: green=completed, blue=current, gray=pending
```

---

## 8. Docker Compose & Production Deployment

### Local Development (`docker-compose.yml`)

```yaml
version: "3.9"
services:
  mongodb:
    image: mongo:latest
    command: ["--replSet", "rs0", "--bind_ip_all"]
    ports: ["27017:27017"]
    volumes: [mongo_data:/data/db]
    healthcheck:
      test: >
        echo 'try { rs.status() } catch(e) { rs.initiate({_id:"rs0",members:[{_id:0,host:"mongodb:27017"}]}) }' | mongosh --quiet
      interval: 10s
      start_period: 30s

  redis:
    image: redis:latest
    ports: ["6379:6379"]
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "redis-cli", "ping"]

  elasticsearch:
    image: elasticsearch:latest
    environment:
      - discovery.type=single-node
      - xpack.security.enabled=false
      - "ES_JAVA_OPTS=-Xms512m -Xmx512m"
    ports: ["9200:9200"]
    volumes: [es_data:/usr/share/elasticsearch/data]
    healthcheck:
      test: curl -s http://localhost:9200/_cluster/health | grep -q '"status":"green\|yellow"'

  minio:
    image: minio/minio:latest
    command: server /data --console-address ":9001"
    ports: ["9000:9000", "9001:9001"]
    environment:
      MINIO_ROOT_USER: minioadmin
      MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD: minioadmin
    volumes: [minio_data:/data]
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "mc", "ready", "local"]
      interval: 10s

  minio-init:
    image: minio/mc:latest
    depends_on:
      minio: { condition: service_healthy }
    entrypoint: >
      /bin/sh -c "
      mc alias set local http://minio:9000 minioadmin minioadmin;
      mc mb --ignore-existing local/product-images;
      mc mb --ignore-existing local/vendor-logos;
      mc mb --ignore-existing local/invoices;
      mc anonymous set download local/product-images;"

  stripe-cli:
    image: stripe/stripe-cli:latest
    command: listen --forward-to http://host.docker.internal:3001/api/v1/webhooks/stripe --api-key $${STRIPE_SECRET_KEY}
    environment:
      STRIPE_SECRET_KEY: ${STRIPE_SECRET_KEY:-sk_test_placeholder}
    extra_hosts:
      - "host.docker.internal:host-gateway"
    depends_on:
      - redis

volumes:
  mongo_data:
  es_data:
  minio_data:
```

> [!NOTE]
> Next.js and NestJS run locally via `pnpm dev` for fast HMR — not containerized during development. The `stripe-cli` container forwards Stripe webhook events to your local NestJS server for testing payment flows end-to-end.

### Production Notes

| Concern               | Solution                                                       |
| --------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Orchestration**     | Kubernetes (EKS/GKE) or ECS Fargate                            |
| **MongoDB**           | Atlas (managed replica set, automated backups, PITR)           |
| **Redis**             | ElastiCache or Redis Cloud                                     |
| **Elasticsearch**     | Elastic Cloud or OpenSearch                                    |
| **MinIO → S3**        | Swap endpoint — same SDK                                       |
| **Secrets**           | AWS Secrets Manager / Vault → injected as env vars             |
| **SSL**               | Terminate at ALB/Ingress with ACM or Let's Encrypt             |
| **CI/CD**             | GitHub Actions → Docker build → ECR → Helm/ArgoCD              |
| **Backups**           | Atlas daily snapshots; S3 versioning + lifecycle; Redis AOF    |
| **Graceful shutdown** | `enableShutdownHooks()` — drain HTTP, close BullMQ, flush logs |

---

## 9. Security Checklist (OWASP + NestJS)

### OWASP Top 10 Coverage

| OWASP Category                    | Mitigation                                                                                                                                                            |
| --------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **A01 Broken Access Control**     | RBAC guards on every route (`@Roles()`), CASL ability checks for resource ownership, tenant isolation (vendor can only see own data)                                  |
| **A02 Cryptographic Failures**    | Bcrypt (cost 12) for passwords, TLS everywhere, `HttpOnly + Secure + SameSite=Lax` cookies, no secrets in client bundles                                              |
| **A03 Injection**                 | `ValidationPipe({ whitelist: true, forbidNonWhitelisted: true })` strips unknown fields, Mongoose schemas enforce types, no `$where` or raw query objects from client |
| **A04 Insecure Design**           | Multi-document transactions for checkout, outbox pattern for reliable events, presigned URLs (no direct upload to server)                                             |
| **A05 Security Misconfiguration** | `helmet()` middleware (HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options), strict CORS origins, disable X-Powered-By                                                      |
| **A06 Vulnerable Components**     | `npm audit` in CI, Dependabot/Renovate for auto-updates, lock file committed                                                                                          |
| **A07 Auth Failures**             | Rate limiting on `/auth/login` (5 attempts/min per IP via `@nestjs/throttler` + Redis), JWT refresh token rotation, short-lived access tokens (15min)                 |
| **A08 Data Integrity**            | Webhook signature verification (HMAC), idempotency keys in `webhook_events`, Stripe webhook signature check                                                           |
| **A09 Logging Failures**          | Audit log for auth events, role changes, payout modifications — written to append-only collection with TTL index                                                      |
| **A10 SSRF**                      | No user-controlled URLs passed to server-side fetch; MinIO endpoint is hardcoded in config                                                                            |

### NestJS-Specific Protections

```typescript
// main.ts
app.use(helmet());
app.enableCors({ origin: [process.env.FRONTEND_URL], credentials: true });
app.useGlobalPipes(
  new ValidationPipe({
    whitelist: true,
    forbidNonWhitelisted: true,
    transform: true,
  }),
);
app.useGlobalInterceptors(new ClassSerializerInterceptor(app.get(Reflector))); // Strip @Exclude() fields
```

### Additional Measures

- **File upload validation:** Presigned URL generation checks MIME type + max file size (5MB images, 20MB invoices). NestJS never touches the file bytes.
- **Rate limiting tiers:** Global (100 req/min), Auth endpoints (5/min), Checkout (10/min), Webhook (1000/min).
- **CSP headers:** Strict Content-Security-Policy via Helmet — `script-src 'self'`, no inline scripts.
- **Audit trail:** `AuditInterceptor` logs `{ action, userId, resource, resourceId, ip, timestamp }` for: login, role change, vendor approval, payout config change, product publish/unpublish.

---

## 10. Observability Plan

### Structured Logging

**Library:** `nestjs-pino` (Pino JSON logger — high performance, structured output).

```typescript
// Every log line includes:
{
  "level": "info",
  "time": 1709136188000,
  "traceId": "abc123...",
  "spanId": "def456...",
  "userId": "user_789",
  "vendorId": "vendor_012",    // null for non-vendor requests
  "method": "POST",
  "url": "/api/v1/orders/checkout",
  "statusCode": 201,
  "responseTime": 342,
  "msg": "Order created successfully"
}
```

**Log levels:**

- `error` — unhandled exceptions, transaction failures, external service errors
- `warn` — retry attempts, rate limit hits, validation failures
- `info` — request/response lifecycle, business events (order created, shipment updated)
- `debug` — cache hit/miss, query timing (disabled in production)

### Metrics (Prometheus)

Expose `/metrics` endpoint via `@willsoto/nestjs-prometheus`.

| Metric                          | Type      | Labels                | Purpose                     |
| ------------------------------- | --------- | --------------------- | --------------------------- |
| `http_request_duration_seconds` | Histogram | method, route, status | API latency SLOs            |
| `http_requests_total`           | Counter   | method, route, status | Traffic volume, error rates |
| `orders_created_total`          | Counter   | vendor_id             | Business metric             |
| `checkout_duration_seconds`     | Histogram | —                     | Checkout performance        |
| `bullmq_queue_depth`            | Gauge     | queue_name            | Queue backlog               |
| `bullmq_job_failed_total`       | Counter   | queue_name            | Worker failures             |
| `mongodb_connection_pool_size`  | Gauge     | —                     | Connection health           |
| `es_index_lag_seconds`          | Gauge     | —                     | Search freshness            |
| `cache_hit_ratio`               | Gauge     | cache_name            | Cache effectiveness         |

### Distributed Tracing (OpenTelemetry)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant B as Browser
    participant NX as Next.js
    participant NS as NestJS
    participant DB as MongoDB
    participant ES as Elasticsearch

    B->>NX: GET /products/wireless-headphones
    Note over NX: Create trace, span: "next.server-component"
    NX->>NS: GET /api/v1/catalog/products/wireless-headphones (traceparent header)
    Note over NS: Child span: "nest.handler"
    NS->>DB: findOne({slug: "wireless-headphones"})
    Note over NS: Child span: "mongodb.query"
    NS-->>NX: 200 OK (product JSON)
    NX-->>B: Rendered HTML
```

**Setup:** `@opentelemetry/sdk-node` + `@opentelemetry/auto-instrumentations-node` in both Next.js and NestJS. Export traces to Jaeger (dev) or Grafana Tempo / Datadog (production).

**`traceparent` propagation:** Next.js `apiFetch` wrapper injects `traceparent` header on every call to NestJS. NestJS `OtelMiddleware` extracts and continues the trace.

### Alerting Thresholds

| Alert                         | Condition                     | Severity    | Action                     |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------------- | ----------- | -------------------------- |
| High API error rate           | >1% 5xx responses over 5min   | 🔴 Critical | Page on-call               |
| Checkout latency              | P95 > 2 seconds over 5min     | 🔴 Critical | Investigate DB/payment     |
| BullMQ dead-letter queue      | Any job in DLQ                | 🟡 Warning  | Investigate + manual retry |
| Queue depth spike             | Any queue > 1000 pending jobs | 🟡 Warning  | Scale workers              |
| MongoDB connection exhaustion | Pool usage > 80%              | 🟡 Warning  | Increase pool size         |
| ES index lag                  | > 60 seconds behind           | 🟡 Warning  | Check outbox poller        |
| Redis memory                  | > 80% max memory              | 🟡 Warning  | Eviction policy review     |
| Disk space (MinIO/S3)         | > 85% capacity                | 🟡 Warning  | Lifecycle cleanup          |

### Per-Component Monitoring Summary

| Component          | What to Watch                                                                    |
| ------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Next.js**        | Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS), ISR cache hit rate, Server Action error rate    |
| **NestJS**         | HTTP latency, error rate, active connections, memory/CPU                         |
| **MongoDB**        | Query slow log (>100ms), connection pool, replication lag, oplog window          |
| **Redis**          | Memory usage, evicted keys, connected clients, BullMQ queue depth                |
| **Elasticsearch**  | Search latency, indexing rate, JVM heap, unassigned shards                       |
| **MinIO/S3**       | Request rate, 4xx errors, storage usage                                          |
| **Stripe**         | Webhook delivery success rate, payment intent failure rate, dispute rate, latency |
| **BullMQ Workers** | Job completion rate, failure rate, processing time, DLQ size                     |

---

_Assumptions made:_

1. _Scale targets hundreds–thousands of vendors, not millions (modular monolith, not day-1 microservices)._
2. _Production MongoDB runs as a managed Atlas Replica Set._
3. _Payment processing via Stripe Connect; shipping via Shippo/EasyPost._
4. _Single geographic region initially; CDN in front of Next.js._
5. _Zod used for validation schema sharing (better TypeScript inference)._
6. _Package manager: **pnpm** throughout (frontend + backend)._
7. _All Docker images use `:latest` tags for local development; production pins to specific versions._
